Performance Analysis and Prediction Between

CPU and GPU for Machine Learning

Introduction¶

In the realm of machine learning, the selection of appropriate hardware plays a pivotal role in attaining peak performance and efficiency. Among the primary computing devices utilized for machine learning tasks, GPUs and CPUs stand out, each showcasing distinct strengths and weaknesses.

Traditionally, CPUs or central processing units have held the preference owing to their versatility and adeptness in multitasking. CPU acts as the computer's brain, executing fundamental instructions such as arithmetic, logic operations, and I/O tasks. On the other hand, a GPU, or graphics processing unit, designed originally for 2D and 3D graphics and specialized in rendering for high-resolution graphics, but these days with the surge in big data and machine learning applications has propelled GPUs into the spotlight, given their capacity to manage extensive datasets and execute parallel computations.

This project aims to delve into the analysis of the variance between GPU and CPU performance by delving into the specifications of the processors, to determine which processors of CPU or GPU provide superior power for machine learning, also which companies have a higher number in manufacturing in these processors and if there are companies manufacturing both of these processors. The last stage of this project is creating a prediction module on the frequency of these processors, and choosing the model that has the higher accuracy in prediction.

About The Dataset¶

This dataset has been collected from Kaggle under the CPU and GPU Performances Dataset topic. It contains 2,185 CPUs and 2,668 GPUs to understand the development trend of CPUs and GPUs and their performance. It encompasses a diverse set of benchmarks and metrics like process size, thermal design power(TDP), die size, number of transistors, and frequency to evaluate the performance of these two types of processors. In addition, the release date and the manufacturer to see the evolution of these processors' performance during these years.

Important Terminology¶

1. Process Size (nm): the size of the transistors used in a processor. The size plays a significant role and typically enables a greater number of transistors to be accommodated within the same physical area (Die Area), potentially leading to enhanced performance, decreased power consumption, and reduced production expenses(nm is an acronym for Nano-meter. It is used to measure microscopic objects or devices like transistors found in processors or atomic structures).

2. Die Size (mm^2): In computing, die refers to the piece of silicon of which the processing unit (a GPU or CPU) consists, often called a chip. Die size means the size of the chunk on a silicon wafer that belongs to one chip. Smaller die sizes allow for more transistors to be packed into the same area resulting in higher processing power and also consuming less power. The number and density of transistors packed into the die determine the processor's computational capacity. (mm^2 is a short form for square millimeters).

3. TDP(W): the electrical energy usage of a computer chip operating at its maximum theoretical load, measured in watts (W).

4. Transistors (million): are minuscule electronic components, that function as switches governing the flow of electricity within a circuit. Within processor architecture, these transistors serve as the foundational elements for constructing logic gates and memory cells, essential components that constitute a processor.

5. Freq (MHz): relates to the clock rate or clock speed at which a processor's clock generator can produce pulses to perform operations within a specified time frame, which is the responsibility of the billions of transistors within the processor to produce these pulses. For instance, a processor operating at a clock speed of 3.2 GHz (3200 MHz) completes 3.2 billion cycles per second.

Since the total missing is around 30% so we have to use the replacing missing values. To use this method missing data should be numeric or categorical value data for replacing them with the mean or mode.

I have decided to proceed with the mean solution to replace the missing values. To fill the missing values by mean, I had to take the average separately for each of these columns (TDP (W), Die Size (mm^2), Transistors (million)) grouped by type of processor (CPU, GPU) to make it more accurate.

TDP (W)¶
In [ ]:
# Take the average of TDP (W) grouped by Type and put it in a variable.
TDP_AVG = dataset.groupby('Type').agg(avg_tdp=('TDP (W)', 'mean')).reset_index()
print(TDP_AVG)

# Create variable to take the CPU (TDP (W)) average only.
cpu_tdp = TDP_AVG.loc[TDP_AVG['Type'] == 'CPU', 'avg_tdp'].values[0]
print(cpu_tdp)

# Create variable to take the GPU (TDP (W)) average only.
gpu_tdp = TDP_AVG.loc[TDP_AVG['Type'] == 'GPU', 'avg_tdp'].values[0]
print(gpu_tdp)

# Replace missing values with the group mean (TDP (W)) of each type of processor.
dataset['TDP (W)'] = dataset.apply(lambda row: cpu_tdp if pd.isna(row['TDP (W)']) and row['Type'] == 'CPU' else (gpu_tdp if pd.isna(row['TDP (W)']) and row['Type'] == 'GPU' else row['TDP (W)']), axis=1)

Data Visualization and Analysis¶

Data visualization is the graphical representation of a dataset in a pictorial format. It is a way to see and understand trends, patterns in data, and outliers. Data visualization is essential to the Analysis for discovering useful information and making findings before prediction.

Types of Processors¶

In [ ]:
data_for_plot = dataset.groupby('Type').size().reset_index(name='Count')

fig = px.pie(data_for_plot, names="Type", values="Count", color_discrete_sequence=["#ffa500", "#0a75ad"])

fig.update_layout(title_text="CPU vs GPU Count Unit", title_x=0.5, title_y=0.98, autosize=False, width=800, height=500)

# Use pyo.iplot to display the figure inline
pyo.iplot(fig)

In this graph, we can see in the provided bar graph that we slightly have more GPUs than CPUs that we'll deal with. We can say that we have a pretty balanced amount of data for both processing units, in which GPUs have 2580 units and CPUs have 2189 units.

First Graph: The Process Size for CPU and GPU evolved similarly with no significant distinction between the two. When we get a closer look at the decade (2000-2010) witness tremendous development compared to the period that followed 2010. However, the overall trend is on consistent decrease in Process Size over time. That is a sign of the integration of more advanced technologies, enabling to achievement of smaller Process Sizes to enhance performance.

Second Graph: For the number of Transistors able to be fit in the processors, we can observe an upward trend indicating for both CPU and GPU from 2008 to 2018, then we have an observable decline in the period between 2018 and 2019 for CPUs and then a slight increase, unlike GPUs have a slight decrease but in 2016 had a massive increase for Transistors numbers. The reason GPUs have more transistors than CPUs, they are hugely different in architecture. CPU is designed with very few cores, but very powerful cores that are extremely complex and can handle all sorts of tasks and complex processes. A GPU is basically designed for parallel computing, to handle parallel processing tasks efficiently, particularly for graphics rendering and parallelizable computing workloads such as those found in machine learning, and that's the reason why GPU is more powerful in machine learning. And despite that, GPUs have thousands of cores but they are much less powerful than those on a CPU.

Third Graph: Looking at this graph for the Frequencies, we can see the big difference in performance between CPUs compared to GPUs with clear superiority CPUs over GPUs. However, both Processing unit seems to have had good development over the years, but the GPUs' improvement is more consistent than the CPUs. Perhaps on this level, GPUs will outperform CPUs in the future in Frequencies.

Fourth Graph: This chart shows us an upward trend in the size of the Die for both CPU and GPU, unless in 2008 there was a decrease in size for the Die Size for CPU, but then returned to an upward trend with the GPU. The big change started in 2015 when each type took its own curve. The Die Size for the GPU started increasing, unlike the Die Size for the CPU, when started to decrease. GPU takes the opposite path of what we said before, that smaller Die Sizes allow for more Transistors resulting in higher processing power also consuming less power. There is another factor number and density of Transistors packed into the Die determine the processor's computational capacity. Later, we will analyze this to discover if the GPU is evolving to higher performance.

Fifth Graph: The TDP(W) started to increase slightly for both CPU and GPU, but after 2006, the gap between them has become large. GPU increased in TDP, but on the other hand the TDP of CPUs decreased until 2009, then started to increase to reach the GPU again in 2016. The huge jump happened in 2021 when the CPU became higher than the GPU. The TDP numbers are affected by several factors, but the most important are the Die Size and the Transistor performance measured by Frequency.

Evaluating Performance¶

Mean Squared Error (MSE):
measures the average of the squares of the errors that is the average squared difference between the estimated values and the actual value.
MSE is always positive and can not be zero either, but the values close to zero are better.

Mean Absolute Error (MAE):

measure of the average size of the mistakes in a collection of predictions, without taking their direction into account.
It is measured the average absolute difference between the predicted values and the actual values.
MAE is always positive and can not be zero either, but the values close to zero are better.

$R^{2}$ (R-squared):
is the proportion of the variation in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable, it is considered another evaluation for the model.
R-squared is comprised between 0 and 1 values closer to 1 are better.

Mean Squared Error (MSE) Mean Absolute Error (MAE) $R^{2}$ (R-squared)
Based on Square of error Based on absolute value of error Based on correlation between actual and predicted value
Value lies between 0 to ∞ Value lies between 0 to ∞ Value lies between 0 and 1
Sensitive to outliers, punches larger error more Treat larger and smaal errors equally. Not sensitive to outliers Not sensitive to outliers
Small value indicates better model Small value indicates better model Value near 1 indicates better model
In [ ]:
mse = mean_squared_error(yTest, y_predLin)
mae = mean_absolute_error(yTest, y_predLin)
r2 = r2_score(yTest, y_predLin)

print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE) for Linear Regression : {mse:.2f}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE) for Linear Regression: {mae:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared Linear Regression: {r2:.2f}")

Mean Squared Error (MSE) for Linear Regression : 0.24
Mean Absolute Error (MAE) for Linear Regression: 0.34
R-squared Linear Regression: 0.79

The MSE is less than the MAE, it means that, on average, the squared errors (MSE) are smaller than the absolute errors (MAE). This mean that the model's predictions have relatively smaller but consistent errors across the dataset.

R-squared value of 0.79, generally considered a good R-squared value, indicating a relatively strong relationship between the predictors and the target variable.

To solve this problem I will tune the model to improving the performance of SVR model by Feature Scaling

Conclusion¶

This project was completed in several stages:¶

First, reading and discovering the data, then cleaning it by dealing with missing data and verifying the format of the data.

Second, visualizing the data and analyzing it, through this analysis I have found these critical findings:

  1. Two major companies, AMD and Intel, are involved in the manufacturing of both CPU and GPU. Intel dominates CPU production, while Nvidia leads in GPU manufacturing. AMD is a significant competitor, ranking second after Intel in CPU production and second after Nvidia in GPU production.

  2. Over time, both CPU and GPU Process Sizes have consistently decreased, with GPUs possessing more transistors due to their parallel computing architecture, particularly advantageous for graphics rendering and machine learning. Despite GPUs having numerous but less powerful cores, CPUs currently exhibit a clear performance superiority. Nevertheless, recent years have shown more consistent improvement in GPUs, raising the possibility of them surpassing CPUs in frequencies in the future. In terms of Die Size, CPUs have experienced a decrease, fostering more transistors and higher processing power, while GPUs have undergone an increase. Smaller Die Sizes contribute to enhanced computational capacity. Regarding Thermal Design Power (TDP), GPU TDP has increased, whereas CPU TDP initially decreased but later rose to levels comparable to GPUs, with TDP influenced by factors such as Die Size and Transistor performance, measured by Frequency.

  3. The density of transistors significantly influences either Frequency, Thermal Design Power (TDP), or both in processors. Development often leans towards prioritizing either power or energy efficiency, with some products excelling in one aspect rather than achieving a balanced performance. Despite CPUs holding a clear overall superiority in both performance and energy consumption, recent years have shown a convergence in processor development. Notably, GPUs are steadily advancing and closing the gap with CPUs, raising the possibility of surpassing them in the future.

Fourth, predictive analysis through this stage chooses the dependent and independent variables and then chooses the right model for prediction which was the Regression model. I had chosen to model from regression Linear and Support Vector. The final result for the best prediction was from the Support Vector after tunning.

The project encountered several challenges along the way:¶

  1. Understanding and navigating the intricate specifications of CPUs and GPUs posed a significant hurdle, given their complex architecture and evolving technologies.

  2. Analyzing and comparing the performance of CPUs and GPUs for machine learning tasks required a deep dive into diverse and technical aspects, including Process Size, Transistor Density, and Die Size.

  3. visualizing this analysis using many libraries for visualization to make it clearer and more understandable.

  4. In the data cleaning section when handling the missing data filling by the means, I used the group for CPU and GPU it belonged for each type of processors not just taking the mean for the column, then creating a column for transistors density to calculate the frequency more accurate for CPU and GPU.

  5. Visualizing the actual frequency with the predicted over time depend on the type of processors done by create new dataframe containing the actual frequency and the predicted meregd with the actual dataframe.

  6. Predicting processor frequencies in the beginning when using Linear was kind of a good performance but when I used Support Vector the performance dropped to the worst thing trying to get a better result using these models by tunning took a while.

Recommendation:¶

I recommend that this data should be more up-to-date and add more specifications for the GPU and CPU to make more analysis between these two processes, especially in the architecture design.
